Psychological symptom reports

Female, 16 - 25 years

Age Reported Symptoms Notes
17 2021-03-03 sleep disorder, impaired work ability Pt reports onset of dizziness, chest tightness, shortness of breath that started acutely 45 minutes ... Read more
Close
Pt reports onset of dizziness, chest tightness, shortness of breath that started acutely 45 minutes to 1 hour after receiving her second Moderna vaccination on 2/24/21. She reported that she was told by her employer that the symptoms were due to the Moderna vaccine. She reportedly developed fever and some throat discomfort as well. Symptoms became persistent and disrupted sleep and was unable to work. She sought medical attention in the ER for persistent symptoms on 2/26/21. Extensive workup was essentially normal. She received Zofran, Decadron, IVFs, and Albuterol inhaler while in the ER. She reported improvement in her chest tightness and SOB after Albuterol. She was discharged home with instructions to f/u with her PCP in a couple of days for recheck.
17 2021-04-22 disturbance in attention The day after the vaccine I felt very weak and fatigued on April 7th. A couple days later on April 9... Read more
Close
The day after the vaccine I felt very weak and fatigued on April 7th. A couple days later on April 9th I developed a fever. A few days after that my muscles started twitching and haven't stopped. I feel like something is crawling under my skin and the vaccine is extremely affecting my nervous system. I did not have this problem before I had the vaccine. It has not gone away and it is now April 23rd I still feel weak, not the same as I used to feel before having the vaccine, and my muscles are twitching all over my body. My face is twitching and my eye and there is nothing I can do to make it stop. I am so young and I thought the vaccine was safe but I am suffering from it. Especially in my feet I feel like they are tingling and vibrating and my calves are convulsing too. Meanwhile, my heart is fluttering and I feel like it is very hard for me to focus and I feel things crawling under my skin in my brain. The muscle convulsions are happening everywhere.
18 2021-01-14 sleep disorder I had no pain or discomfort immediately after the shot, during the 15 minute observation period, or ... Read more
Close
I had no pain or discomfort immediately after the shot, during the 15 minute observation period, or an hour after. About 2 hours later (at 2:00 pm), I developed some hives around my neck, and the part of my arm near the injection site started to become more and more sore. I applied Benadryl to the hives and they went away. However, my left arm hurt to touch or move, much worse than any vaccine I've had before (flu, HPV). That night, I had trouble sleeping because the discomfort because of the sore left arm. I also could not sleep because of chest tightness and pressure, which worsened when lying down, but that pressure did not progress to the point of wheezing (I have asthma). Sleeping on my back was the only option because sleeping on either side was painful, which worsened the chest pressure. When I woke up, my fingers felt stiff and I had joint pain in both hands, more so in my left hand. Throughout this, I did not see any redness on my arm. This day it was agonizing to move my left arm. I could pick things up, but raising it above my the height of my waist or twisting it behind my back to get on my backpack was near impossible and was avoided. The chest pressure went away. The second night, I still had trouble sleeping, but the pain was much better, although I still could not sleep on my side. When I woke up, I had no more joint pain. That day, although the left arm was still sore, I could move it pretty well. If I made too strong of a movement, it felt like the injection site would tense up, the pain would slowly ramp up, and then diminish. That afternoon, at 4:30, I was able to play tennis with minimal soreness, and that night, I was able to sleep on my side. The following day, I had a cough, but that might have been because I didn't dress for the weather, and experiences close to zero soreness.

patient was shaky and laid on the floor for 20 minutes after with feet elevated. patient had no further issues.

Shot was given at 4:00pm on a Tuesday. That evening around 9:00pm patient was nauseas. Went to bed and couldn't sleep because entire body hurt. Vomited at 9:00am the next day(Wednesday) and had a fever 101.3F, chills, muscle pain on entire body and a headache. Called into work and laid in bed all day. Heart rate was 120bpm (typically it is around 70bmp). Took Tylenol which brought the fever down at 5:00pm. Finally was able to eat something. Took more Tylenol before bed and was able to sleep. Woke up Thursday and still felt achy but functional with a headache and nausea. Same symptoms minus the nausea on Friday.

Given zyrtec. Not SOB and not wheezing, no rash or objective swelling of the face or oropharynx. The nurse reports that she cannot move her tongue very well. 18 2021-03-10 anxiety 18 year old female came to hospital for chest tightness, choking sensation in the throat as well as ... Read more
Close
18 year old female came to hospital for chest tightness, choking sensation in the throat as well as skin rash after receiving COVID-19 vaccine. Initially patient presented to emergency room but subsequently discharged on steroid and Benadryl. Patient had continued episode of choking as well as chest tightness and skin rash for that patient came back to emergency room. Patient had received total 5 doses of epi pen because of that. Patient was admitted to medical floor initially. Patient was given steroid, Benadryl and famotidine. Patient had 2 episodes on medical floor where she started feeling choking and chest tightness. Patient remained stable hemodynamically except for tachycardia. Patient was transferred to intensive care unit for close monitoring. D-dimer was negative, urine tox screen was negative, COVID-19 PCR was negative, EKG showed sinus tachycardia. CT scan of neck was negative. We had discussed that patient has remained stable hemodynamically in the intensive care unit and discharge planning was discussed and patient was getting ready to be discharged when she had another episode where after drinking soda patient started having that choking sensation, patient remained stable hemodynamically during this episode as well. Her symptoms had improved. She looked visibly anxious. Patient was monitored in the ICU for few more hours and patient remained stable. I checked back on her and she was able to eat her lunch. She probably had a allergic reaction to more than a vaccine but subsequent episodes are thought to be secondary to anxiety attack given situation.

Close
Pt received vaccination at 1:30pm, pt ambulated to observation area, began feeling "dizzy and nauseous" while standing in observation area. Pt ambulated to chair, at which time pt lost consciousness and her body became stiff, gagging sounds noted. Removed pt's mask, applied oxygen at 10l/min via face mask. pt regained consciousness within 30 -60 seconds. Vital signs BP 124/82, unable to assess sp02 due to cold fingers and nail polish. HR 102. Pt stated she continued to feel dizzy, and had tingling in her fingers. Vital signs reassessed at 1:43, BP 128/78, HR 80, unable to asses sp02 due to monitor not giving a reading. Vitals reassessed at 1:46pm, sp02 100%, HR 94. , began titrating oxygen supply down by 2l/min. Pt seemed to tolerate well for a few minutes, At 2:00pm, pt complained of tingling returning to her fingers, pt was receiving o2 4l/min, sp02 noted at 80%, increased 02 to 10l/min, called nursing lead who called 911. 2:10, unable to obtain accurate sp02. 2:17pm pt continues to receive 02 10l/min, stated she "feels okay, just weird and foggy" no tingling in hands. 2:20pm, paramedics arrive, pt states she is "a little bit dizzy" 2:35pm pt taken to hospital via stretcher with paramedics. Pt en route to hospital. At 2:00pm sp02 80%

18 2021-03-16 loss of personal independence in daily activities Approximately 7-8 minutes after receiving the vaccine, started to feel light-headed, thought she was... Read more
Close
Approximately 7-8 minutes after receiving the vaccine, started to feel light-headed, thought she was going to pass out, and her heart was racing extremely high. The health care team at the site took her blood pressure, measured heart rate, gave her water, juice and chocolate and tried to get her heart rate to drop. It was fluctuating up and down and she couldn't stand up without dizziness; we waited 45 minutes and then drove her home as she was unable to drive her own car. She was experiencing significant lightheadedness, and consistent heart racing even while lying down on the sofa/bed. This continued for several days and she stayed home from school and sports. We called her primary care doctor on the 10th and they suggested she wait another day to see how she was feeling. She started to feel a bit better by Friday, was still experiencing a bit of the tiredness, nauseous, light-headed and heart spikes, but was able to drive, move around. On Sunday evening, she started to experience increased heart rate again, lymph nodes were very painful and started experiencing the light headedness all evening. On Monday we took her to her primary care provider and they then referred her to ER for the heart racing and a EKG. The increased light headedness, feeling like she will pass out even while laying in bed, dizziness has all increased and her lymph nodes continue to be swollen and painful. It has been over a week since the vaccine and there is no clear sign of her reaction getting any better, if not worse. The EKG results indicated a new abnormality and we are trying to get her to a cardiologist. She is and had been a very healthy, varsity athlete that runs over 30 hours a week with track, and since receiving the first dose of the Moderna vaccine is unable to move very far within the house without feeling that she is going to pass out or that her heart rate is shooting up uncontrollably.

Complaining top of head hurts. Client reports she has not eaten today, as she indicated she was very anxious about getting the covid immunization and reports she did not sleep last night. Next page15:39: BP 110/65, pulse 87 15:41: BP 119/77, pulse 91 15:47: BP 110/77, pulse 88 15:50--paramedics started IV and checked blood sugar at 103. Client very anxious, but agreed to be tranported to ER due to hit to head. Local transport unit called. 16:01: BP 98/64, pulse 76. 16:03: EMS transport unit arrived/transported to Emergency Room.

18 2021-04-07 incoherent Initially she passed out following the vaccine - within 90 seconds- she has a history of passing out... Read more
Close
Initially she passed out following the vaccine - within 90 seconds- she has a history of passing out with injections and blood draws. Around noon she had a seizure. She describes a feeling of darkness and dread closing in on her and she was unable to speak or move. She was on the stairs at the time. I witnessed her stiffen, then go limp and fall between the electric stair hair and the wall. She hit the hardwood floor face first then she began to shake/twitch. She was unconscious. She awoke screaming, incoherent speech, and flailing limbs. It took about 5 minutes to calm her and be able to understand her speech. She only remembers the darkness and waking up scared and feeling awful. She was put supine on the floor with feet elevated, blood pressure monitored, given juice to drink, and vitals checked routinely. After about an hour supine and conscious, she felt good enough to sit up. She sat up for 15 minutes before she was able to stand with assistance. Family physician was notified immediately and we are still waiting for a response. She has a goose egg sized knot on her forehead, a bruise on the side of her face and a black eye from hitting the floor. She has a huge bruise on her outer thigh and lower leg where she hit the stair chair and then seized and it it repeatedly on the metal. She has underarm pain from where her armpit hit the edge of the stairs when she fell and seized. She has no history of any types of seizures.

18 2021-04-07 sleep disorder About 72 hours after her 2nd Moderna vaccine, patient developed an uncommon condition known as Lipsc... Read more
Close
About 72 hours after her 2nd Moderna vaccine, patient developed an uncommon condition known as Lipschutz ulcers. It is a non sexually transmitted condition characterized by the rapid onset of painful, necrotic ulcerations of the vulva or lower vagina. Pt presented with moderate unilateral labial swelling, several vulvar ulcers noted to inner labia minora with yellow/bloody discharge. Some ulcers with necrotic appearing tissue. Extremely tender to touch. Pt without hx of EBV infection.

18 2021-04-26 anxiety Patient had felt nervous prior to getting her 2nd shot. I asked if she had every had any serious rea... Read more
Close
Patient had felt nervous prior to getting her 2nd shot. I asked if she had every had any serious reactions from previous medicines or vaccines, she stated "no". I then asked how she did after her first shot and she said ok. While waiting her 15 min in the observation area she alerted us that she was feeling extremely hot. We brought her back into the IMZ booth and had her sit in the chair and turned a fan in her direction. I sat down with her an asked her questions and kept her talking to try to calm her down. She stated that she felt as if the chair was swaying a little. We laid out a yoga mat on the floor in the booth, had her lay down and elevate her feet in a chair. She began to get upset and I asked if she had anyone with her, she was able to open her phone and gave me permission to call her family member. Family member came in the store and was able to help calm her down. We gave her some water and had her rest. I monitored her pulse and face/lip color. She became a little flushed. She was able to leave on her own accord, I did walk out with her to ensure she made it safely. I called 2 hours later to check on her and she stated she was feeling better, less dizzy, but just a little tired.

Seven hours after receiving my second dose, I developed flu-like symptoms--fever of 100-101 degrees, full body aches, fatigue, and chills, in addition to a sore left arm. These symptoms continued for 18 hours. It was difficult to sleep. I had the flu three years ago but this felt more severe. Symptoms were treated first with 200mg ibuprofen with no response and then with Tylenol, which improved symptoms. I stayed in bed for most of those 18 hours to rest. Two days after receiving my second dose, I had a headache for the whole day. The headache then became a migraine. Both treated with aspirin. Three days after the second dose, I felt fatigued, weak, and still had a headache. To my understanding, the first two days of ailment reflect my body's immune response and the final two are typical of my body's stress response. However, I have not experienced either in response to a vaccine. I should also mention my first menstrual cycle after receiving the first dose of the vaccine was shorter than usual. My periods are not always regular so it may be a coincidence, not causation.

A few days after she started to notice axillary pain that progressed up her right neck and down to her right hand. She saw a physician who thought she was having nerve pain brought on by the vaccine. Around the 18th she started to feel a snapping pain in her wrist. Went to ED on the 20th because she started to have arm shaking, she was given ativan, her arm shaking stopped and they discharged her home. That evening her fingers felt clenched. On the 21st she woke up in the morning, went to urinate and dropped to the floor because her legs felt like jello and felt like they kept giving out. They initially thought the ativan was just making her feel out of it. They waited until the evening but then needed to go to the ED. The concern was GBS and transverse myelitis. They ate dinner and decided to drive to ED, on the drive she was kind of falling asleep periodically. Then she suddenly couldn't lift her water bottle. She started to be completely out of it, Mom says she wasn't responding. Pt says that she felt like she knew what was going on, felt a little out of body and wasn't quite responding. Mom couldn't get her out of the car, she was carried into the ED and at that point she started to recover a little bit more. About 10 minutes later she started to feel better. She was admitted because she was still having trouble walking. In the hospital she had a normal CT head and video EEG but she didn't have any events while on the monitor. Discharged home the following day with the diagnosis of functional neurologic disorder and instructions to establish care with an adult PCP. They advised considering CBT as well. Since discharge her legs feels tired, going up the stairs feels much harder than it should. She has not had any falls and no longer feels like she is going to fall. She follows with a therapist, has had dissociative episodes and panic attacks in the past. Assessment: 20 YOF with PMH of panic attack, POTS, IDA and benign heart murmur who developed weakness of b/l LE and altered consciousness approximately 10 days after her first dose of Moderna COVID vaccine. Also had an episode of unilateral arm shaking the day prior that resolved with ativan in the ED. At this point unclear if directly related to vaccination. Differential includes mild Guillain-Barre 2/2 previous infection or vaccination, stress reaction/anxiety, POTS complication, myasthenia gravis, tick bite, infection, heavy metal poisoning, B12 deficiency, seizure disorder, atypical migraine. Functional Neurologic Disorder diagnosed by neurology after overnight admission for video EEG which captured no events. CT head also WNL per neurology discharge summary. Neurologic exam today WNL. After Second Vaccine: History: She had her 2nd vaccine on 4/15 (6 days ago). Had vaccine in right arm again, she did have some arm pain again. She had coffee without breakfast in the morning. Had finished her first virtual class, went to the restroom during her second class, felt strangely in the restroom, went back to her room. She then passed out. Her fall was unwitnessed. She called to her roommate when she came to but her roommate hadn't heard the fall. She thinks she was only out for a few seconds but cannot be sure. Called her Mom who advised her to eat something so she ate an orange sitting on the floor. She got up to make herself breakfast and she passed out again. Again unwitnessed but patient thinks it was very fast. She crawled over to the couch, sat on the couch for for 15 minutes then felt fine for the rest of the day. She did not feel nauseous at all. She denies palpitations, difficulty breathing and chest pain. Today in office after orthostatics and blood draw she fainted again, only out for seconds. BP elevated immediately after the event but WNL minutes later. These syncopal episodes reminded her of her syncopal episodes with IDA and POTS. They do not feel like the episode after the first vaccine when she lost feeling in her legs and was very out of it. She feels like her arm pain from the first vaccine never fully resolved. After the arm pain worsened from the 2nd shot she tried a 3 day course of aleve to see if that helped things. At this point it is mostly just her right wrist that is painful. Overall feels more localized to wrist than prior. She has since stopped the aleve, last was last night. She has not noticed redness or swelling in wrist or arm. LMP was 4/2-4/6. 21 2021-03-25 disorientation I received an allergy immunotherapy shot the day before my first dose of the vaccine and instantly f... Read more
Close
I received an allergy immunotherapy shot the day before my first dose of the vaccine and instantly felt nauseous and extremely tired after receiving the vaccine, which continued for two days after receiving tut. Three days later, I woke up struggling to breathe (but not anaphylactic), covered in hives, itchy all over, shaking, disoriented, and chilled but not truly feverish. I reported this to my allergist, who prescribed prednisone and suggested the vaccine combined with immunotherapy were too much for my immune system for one week. The hives, itchiness, and difficulty breathing lasted about four days. I struggled with fatigue and nausea for over two weeks, stopping all school and work in the meantime. After my second dose, I feel just a bit tired and sore, so I think this truly was a bad reaction to the two injections combined rather than to the vaccine itself. Still, it was a debilitating experience, and I would recommend considering putting out guidance that other immunotherapy patients space out their allergy injections and vaccines farther than I did.

Close
The date of the second dose was 05/25/2021, which is when the side effects started. I had the normal and expected effects, such as a sore arm and fatigue. I began my period that morning, before I went in for the shot. I would like to be as detailed as possible, so I will likely include some graphic details in this description. My apologies in advance. My period normally lasts 3-4 days and is moderate (as far as I know) regarding blood loss. After the second dose, the flow was extremely heavy and my period lasted for almost an entire week (7 days). It was miserable. I was bloated and tender in that area, and extremely tired. I was also cramping, which is unusual for me nowadays. About two weeks after that, I felt a stabbing or ripping pain in the uterus area. It stayed for about two days, throbbing every minute or so. I could not sleep those days. It was not so unbearable that I could not perform everyday actions, but it was taking up a good portion of my thoughts that weekend. After that, it went away and I thought it was over. About three days ago from today (today is June 22nd, or 06/22/2021), the pain returned and I knew it meant the start of my period. The timing was normal. The next day I began bleeding, but the flow is again much heavier than normal. The pain is back and much worse than before. I am going through many more pads than usual and it is, for me, a worrying amount of blood. Since this is the second period in a row I am experiencing this, I felt it was necessary to report it in. I hope this is okay and not taking resources from those with worse issues. I would also like to note that I experienced my first panic attack in 5 years the night of my second dose (for no reason- they've always had a concrete reason for occurring) and my anxiety was notably worse that week (I am on medication and was otherwise doing very well managing the anxiety). During the attack I experienced the usual symptoms: my throat closing up and making it harder to breathe, and uncontrollable shaking and crying. I was not thinking of anything that would make me nervous at the time of the attack. I had just finished an online gaming session with a friend and was showering to prepare for bed, so I was fully relaxed. Additionally, my mental health has notably dipped a bit over the last month, though there are a number of factors at play and I don't want to blame the vaccine for that. However, I was told to at least make note of it here just in case there does end up being a correlation.

The patient's medical history was not provided. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter. On 06 Jan 2021, the patient received her first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 intramuscularly in her right deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 06 Jan 2021, the patient experienced a sore arm, fever, chills, itching and burning. On 07 Jan 2021, on the site where the patient received the injection, she felt numbness and weak. Her whole right-side body would jerk uncontrollably. The patient went to two emergency rooms where they stated they did not know what was wrong and gave her a steroid injection that temporarily helped calm her down. On 08 Jan 2021, the patient stared at the door and everything went blank. She could not talk and when she tried to talk, she felt like she had the hiccups. She experienced her whole chest hurting when she had a hiccup. On 25 Jan 2021 and 26 Jan 2021, the patient saw two neurologists, who did testing. The patient's jerking was random, there were no triggers for it, and she did not know how to control or stop it. These adverse reactions made the patient become aggravated very quickly, which was not like her. On an unknown date, the patient stated it was the first day in the past month she had been able to talk all day. Treatment for the events included a steroid shot. Action taken with the second dose of mRNA-1273 in response to the event was not reported. The outcome for the events, sore arm/ burning, fever, chills, itching, numbness, weak, whole right side would jerk uncontrollably, everything went blank, couldn't talk and when she tried to talk she felt like she had the hiccups and her whole chest hurt, and quickly became aggravated, was not reported.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information which indicates a strong temporal association between the use of the product and the onset of the reported events a causal relationship cannot be excluded. Chills, fever, injection site pruritus and injection site pain are consistent with the known safety profile of mRNA-1273.

As of today, I am still having a very hard time taking a full, deep breath and continue to have pressure in my chest.

I am still prone to "attacks" where the tics become very severe and debilitating to the point where I cannot work. pounding heart, heart rate increased; panic; Total body flushing; Sensation of hot and cold; Shaking; lightheadedness; feelings of passing out; nausea; arm numbness; extremity tingling; headache; exhaustion; fever; fluctuating blood pressure; racing heart ,heart palpitations; mild flushing; brain fog; A spontaneous report was received from a healthcare professional concerning a 25-years-old, female patient, who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced panic, rapid pulse, pounding heart, total body flushing, shaking, a sensation of hot and cold, lightheadedness, and feelings of passing out, nausea, extremity tingling, and arm numbness, headache, brain fog, racing heart, heart palpitations, fluctuating blood pressure, mild flushing, exhaustion, and fever. The patient's medical history, was not provided by the reporter, but patient had a tuberculosis test done in recent days prior to vaccination, reports were not provided. Concomitant medications reported included vitamin B-12 complex and ibuprofen. On 04-Mar-2021 at 5:55 pm, prior to the onset of the events, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 013A21A) intramuscularly in the deltoid for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection. On 04 Mar 2021, approximately after 23 minutes after receiving the vaccine patient developed panic, rapid pulse, pounding heart, total body flushing, shaking, a sensation of hot and cold, lightheadedness, and feelings of passing out. Patient pulled over and called 9-1-1, and she was taken by ambulance to a nearby hospital. Patient had reported that the symptoms persisted during ambulance transit and continued during her three hour hospital stay. Patient reported to have development of nausea, extremity tingling, and arm numbness while being admitted. Patient reported that a friend of her drove her home from the hospital, and her brother was monitoring her condition. No medicinal treatments were administered at the hospital for the patient. On 05 Mar 2021, Patient took advil to treat the headache and brain fog that has developed. Patient reported that the symptoms headache, brain fog, racing heart, heart palpitations, fluctuating blood pressure, mild flushing, exhaustion, and fever were continuing. As treatment for events no medicinal treatments were administered at the hospital. Patient reported that she had taken ibuprofen to treat a headache and brain fog. Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown. The outcome of events, panic, rapid pulse, pounding heart, total body flushing, shaking, a sensation of hot and cold, lightheadedness, and feelings of passing out, nausea, extremity tingling, and arm numbness was unknown and headache, brain fog, racing heart, heart palpitations, fluctuating blood pressure, mild flushing, exhaustion, and fever were not recovered.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.

Close
Around 6:00 pm on the day of vaccination I started to feel very fatigued and developed body aches - this felt similar to the beginning of developing Covid-19 symptoms. (I had Covid-19 back in November of 2020) Around 8:00 pm I had developed some head congestion and swollen lymph nodes along with some throat pain and sinus congestion - again feeling very similar to Covid-19 symptoms. Around 10:00 pm as I was heading to bed the symptoms became a lot worse, I had pretty intense body aches and started to experience chills as well as a slight fever (around 99.5 in F). At this time the symptoms felt similar to how I had felt during the worst of my previous Covid-19 symptoms, very weak and achy, headache was very bad, and felt very uncomfortable overall. Around 2:00 am on March 13 I woke up with a fever of 101.8. The previous symptoms had also gotten worse, I was having a hard time getting out of bed because things were very uncomfortable, I drank a lot of water and took some ibuprofen to combat the fever, about an hour after this the fever had come down to about 99.9 and I was able to fall asleep, but before taking the medication I couldn't have fallen asleep because of the discomfort of the aches, chills, and fever. Throughout the following day I was unable to complete many of my day to day activities without taking a daytime cold and flu medication. With the medication I still felt sick but was able to walk around and complete some simple household chores, this carried through into the evening, when the medication wore off the chills and aches and headache were much worse and I still had a fever around 99-100. That night I was able to sleep with the cold and flu medication taken right before bed. Upon waking up the next morning (March 14) I still had some congestion, headache, and general discomfort but the worst of the aches were gone and I no longer had a fever, these symptoms continued to diminish throughout the day. On March 15 and March 16th I have had a slight lingering congestion headache, this also feels really similar to the lingering headache I had upon recovering from Covid-19. It is not debilitating and is continuing to improve. Otherwise I am feeling healthy again and have been able to complete my usual activities and even exercise. Overall the symptoms felt like a couple days of having Covid-19 again, but recovery was much faster, and it was definitely worth receiving that first dose of the vaccine and getting started with the process of doing my part to reduce community spread.
